<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-357-549  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 357 549.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IBM System User  June 1990 p30(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>High-fibre diet. (Fiber Distributed Data Interface opticalcommunications technology offers high bandwidth capacity to localarea networks)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sweet, Pat.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Fiber Distributed Data Interface (FDDI) fiber optic networkingtechnology offers 100M-bits/second data transfer capability overlocal area networks (LANs), but potential users should be aware ofthe current high costs and be careful that the technology conformsto developing FDDI standards to ensure communication betweenmultivendor products.andP;  FDDI multimode optical fiber can supportLAN distances of up to 200km or a dual token-ring LAN of 100km.andO;The standard consists of four main parts, with only threedeveloped to draft status (Physical Medium Dependent, PhysicalLayer Protocol and Media Access Control) plus Station Management,due in the summer of 1990.andP;  Many vendors are waiting forresolution of the standards, but 'FDDI products should beappearing by the end of' 1990.andP;  These include bridges to variousnetwork technologies, routers and concentrators.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber Distributed Data Interface StandardOutlookProduct DevelopmentTechnologyApplicationsStandardsLocal Area NetworksSystem Development.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>